’ 239. Distinguish between an Indirect Question and a question in Indirect Discourse. The former is the subject or (more usually) the object of a verb of asking, and is regularly expressed in the subjunctive mood. (Cf. see. 116.) The latter is a question trans· ferred from direct to indirect discourse after a verb of saying or thinking. For example, the rhetorian question, can I forget ,Ι num oblivisci possum! becomes in indirect discourse, hc says, can he forget? dicit num oblivisci εξ posse.
